Let's check the overall distribution of Patient Age as compared to that of Pneumonic Patients¶

OBSERVATIONS:¶

From the above information gathered about the 'PatientAge' column, we are able to gather the following insights:¶

  • The distribution plot indicates that 'PatientAge' attribute is normally distributed with mean and median values almost coinciding.
  • As mean is slightly to the left of the median value, the distribution is negatively skewed with skewness value of -0.23.
  • 25% each of values lie at less than 34 and more than 59, while 50% of the values lie between 34 and 59.
  • The distribution has a range of 154 with minimum and maximum values of 1 and 155 respectively.
  • Approximately 95% of values lie between 13.02 and 80.58 (Mean+/-2 std deviations)
  • The boxplot indicates the presence of some outlier age values above 100 years which seems unrealistic. Upon inspection it was found that there were 5 age values in the range of 148-155 years. This could be due to some processing error and must be addressed before passing the data to the model.
  • Maximum number of positive pneumonia cases were observed for patients in the age of 54 years.

In [26]:
#Checking the number and percentage of instances in each class

def get_feature_distribution(data, feature):
    # Get the count for each label
    label_counts = df[feature].value_counts()

    # Get total number of samples
    total_samples = len(df)

    # Count the number of items in each class
    print("Feature: {}".format(feature))
    for i in range(len(label_counts)):
        label = label_counts.index[i]
        count = label_counts.values[i]
        percent = int((count / total_samples) * 10000) / 100
        print("{:<30s}:   {} or {}%".format(label, count, percent))

get_feature_distribution(df, 'class')

Normal                        :   8851 or 33.16%

10. CREATING AND ANALYSING NEW FEATURE : SEVERITY SCORE¶

Our dataset can be trained to perform the qualitative analysis of Pneumonia by classifying whether the patient (based on their X-Ray Scan) is having Pneumonia or not. Also, the model can be trained to localise the opacities and show them with the help of bounding boxes.¶

We propose to add another dimension in the dataset which could help us perform the quantitative analysis on the X-Ray Image. It can tell how severe the patient is infected with the help of a parameter called 'Severity Score'.¶

This severity score shall be directly proportional to the intensity of lungs infection and could accordingly help the physician determine the course of treatment.¶

This way the doctors would be able to clinically correlate the score with the patient's condition and decide whether the patient can be home treated or needs hospitalization. Also, unnecessary under-use or over-use of prescription drugs may be avoided and the patient can be treated in a more objective manner.¶

We propose to use the bounding box parameters, namely 'height' and 'width' to calculate the area of each box.¶

Next we shall determine the number of bounding boxes for each patient.¶

As is obvious, a more severe patient shall have larger bounding box areas, meaning larger opaque areas. Also, apart from size of the box, their numbers per X-ray image shall have a bearing on the severity.¶

Instead of using each of these parameters independently, we propose to add the areas of all the bounding boxes for a unique patient id to reach to a robust indicator of severity, which we shall call 'Severity Score'.¶

First of all we shall calculate the areas of individual bounding boxes by multiplying their width with the corresponding height. For this we shall create a dataset 'df2' by taking relevant columns from dataset 'df1'.¶
